{{Infobox settlement | official_name = Martin-de-Viviès | native_name = | other_name = Camp Heurtin | settlement_type = Village | image_skyline = AmsterdamIsl Map.png | imagesize = | image_caption = Amsterdam Island, with Martin-de-Viviès at the northern end | image_flag = | image_seal = | image_map = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_label_position = bottom | pushpin_mapsize = 300 | coordinates = {{coord|37|47|48|S|77|34|23|E|region:FR|display=inline,title}} | subdivision_type = Country | subdivision_name = [[France]] | subdivision_type1 = [[Overseas territory (France)|Territory]] | subdivision_name1 = [[French Southern and Antarctic Lands]] (TAAF) | subdivision_type2 = District | subdivision_name2 = [[Île Amsterdam]] | established_title = | established_date = 1 January 1981 | leader_title = | leader_name = | unit_pref = Imperial | area_total_km2 = | area_land_km2 = | elevation_footnotes = | elevation_m = | population_footnotes = | population_total = | population_as_of = | population_density_km2 = | timezone = | utc_offset = | postal_code_type = | postal_code = | area_code = | website = }} '''Martin-de-Viviès''', or '''La Roche Godon''', formerly '''Camp Heurtin''', is a [[research station]] and the only settlement on the [[Île Amsterdam]] and [[Île Saint-Paul]] islands of the [[French Southern and Antarctic Lands]] in the southern [[Indian Ocean]]. It lies on the north coast of Amsterdam Island and houses about thirty people.<ref>{{cite web|last1=kuschk|title=Île Amsterdam: Isolated in the Indian Ocean|url=http://basementgeographer.com/ile-amsterdam-isolated-in-the-indian-ocean/|website=The Basement Geographer|accessdate=10 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220063334/http://basementgeographer.com/ile-amsterdam-isolated-in-the-indian-ocean/|archivedate=December 20, 2016|date=March 8, 2012}}</ref>
It was named after [[Paul de Martin de Viviès]] who, with ten others, spent the winter of 1949 on the island.
The station was originally named Camp Heurtin and has been in operation since 1 January 1981, superseding the first station, La Roche Godon.
The [[Global Atmosphere Watch]] is one of the programs that the station participates in.{{cn|date=October 2018}}
